void USBUART_CD_Dp_SetDriveMode (uint8 mode)
 Sets the drive mode for each of the Pins component's pins. More...
 
uint8 USBUART_CD_Dp_ReadDataReg (void)
 Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance. More...
 
uint8 USBUART_CD_Dp_Read (void)
 Reads the associated physical port (pin status register) and masks the required bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance. More...
 
void USBUART_CD_Dp_SetInterruptMode (uint16 position, uint16 mode)
 Configures the interrupt mode for each of the Pins component's pins. Alternatively you may set the interrupt mode for all the pins specified in the Pins component. More...
 
uint8 USBUART_CD_Dp_ClearInterrupt (void)
 Clears any active interrupts attached with the component and returns the value of the interrupt status register allowing determination of which pins generated an interrupt event. More...

◆ BP_3V_Sel_In_ClearInterrupt()

uint8 BP_3V_Sel_In_ClearInterrupt ( void  )

◆ BP_3V_Sel_In_Read()

uint8 BP_3V_Sel_In_Read ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port (pin status register) and masks the required bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: BP_3V_Sel_In_Read

The pin's status register returns the current logic level present on the physical pin.

Returns
The current value for the pins in the component as a right justified number.

\funcusage

Definition at line 113 of file BP_3V_Sel_In.c.

◆ BP_3V_Sel_In_ReadDataReg()

uint8 BP_3V_Sel_In_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: BP_3V_Sel_In_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred BP_3V_Sel_In_Read() API because the BP_3V_Sel_In_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Definition at line 141 of file BP_3V_Sel_In.c.

◆ BP_3V_Sel_In_SetDriveMode()

void BP_3V_Sel_In_SetDriveMode ( uint8  mode)

Sets the drive mode for each of the Pins component's pins.

Function Name: BP_3V_Sel_In_SetDriveMode

Note This affects all pins in the Pins component instance. Use the Per-Pin APIs if you wish to control individual pin's drive modes.

Parameters
modeMode for the selected signals. Valid options are documented in Drive mode constants.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic, the ISR can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component Drive Mode registers can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

◆ BP_3V_Sel_In_Write()

void BP_3V_Sel_In_Write ( uint8  value)

Writes the value to the physical port (data output register), masking and shifting the bits appropriately.

File Name: BP_3V_Sel_In.c
Version 2.20

Description: This file contains API to enable firmware control of a Pins component.

Note:

Copyright 2008-2015, Cypress Semiconductor Corporation. All rights reserved. You may use this file only in accordance with the license, terms, conditions, disclaimers, and limitations in the end user license agreement accompanying the software package with which this file was provided. Function Name: BP_3V_Sel_In_Write

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This function avoids changing other bits in the port by using the appropriate method (read-modify-write or bit banding).

Note This function should not be used on a hardware digital output pin as it is driven by the hardware signal attached to it.

Parameters
valueValue to write to the component instance.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic; the Interrupt Service Routines (ISR) can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component data register can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

Definition at line 57 of file BP_3V_Sel_In.c.

valueValue to write to the component instance.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic; the Interrupt Service Routines (ISR) can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component data register can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

Definition at line 113 of file Pin_Baro1PresBP.c.

◆ Pin_Baro1PresBP_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_Baro1PresBP_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_Baro1PresBP_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_Baro1PresBP_Read() API because the Pin_Baro1PresBP_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Description: This file contains API to enable firmware control of a Pins component.

Note:

Copyright 2008-2015, Cypress Semiconductor Corporation. All rights reserved. You may use this file only in accordance with the license, terms, conditions, disclaimers, and limitations in the end user license agreement accompanying the software package with which this file was provided. Function Name: Pin_BaroPres_Write

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This function avoids changing other bits in the port by using the appropriate method (read-modify-write or bit banding).

Note This function should not be used on a hardware digital output pin as it is driven by the hardware signal attached to it.

Parameters
valueValue to write to the component instance.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic; the Interrupt Service Routines (ISR) can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component data register can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

Definition at line 57 of file Pin_BaroPres.c.

◆ Pin_BaroTemp2_ClearInterrupt()

uint8 Pin_BaroTemp2_ClearInterrupt ( void  )

◆ Pin_BaroTemp2_Read()

uint8 Pin_BaroTemp2_Read ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port (pin status register) and masks the required bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_BaroTemp2_Read

The pin's status register returns the current logic level present on the physical pin.

Returns
The current value for the pins in the component as a right justified number.

\funcusage

Definition at line 113 of file Pin_BaroTemp2.c.

◆ Pin_BaroTemp2_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_BaroTemp2_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_BaroTemp2_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_BaroTemp2_Read() API because the Pin_BaroTemp2_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Definition at line 141 of file Pin_BaroTemp2.c.

◆ Pin_BaroTemp2_SetDriveMode()

void Pin_BaroTemp2_SetDriveMode ( uint8  mode)

Sets the drive mode for each of the Pins component's pins.

Function Name: Pin_BaroTemp2_SetDriveMode

Note This affects all pins in the Pins component instance. Use the Per-Pin APIs if you wish to control individual pin's drive modes.

Parameters
modeMode for the selected signals. Valid options are documented in Drive mode constants.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic, the ISR can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component Drive Mode registers can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

◆ Pin_HRRx2_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_HRRx2_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_HRRx2_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_HRRx2_Read() API because the Pin_HRRx2_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Function Name: Pin_HRRx2_SetDriveMode

Note This affects all pins in the Pins component instance. Use the Per-Pin APIs if you wish to control individual pin's drive modes.

Parameters
modeMode for the selected signals. Valid options are documented in Drive mode constants.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic, the ISR can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component Drive Mode registers can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

◆ Pin_LRTx2_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_LRTx2_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_LRTx2_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_LRTx2_Read() API because the Pin_LRTx2_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Definition at line 141 of file Pin_LRTx2.c.

◆ Pin_LRTx2_SetDriveMode()

void Pin_LRTx2_SetDriveMode ( uint8  mode)

Sets the drive mode for each of the Pins component's pins.

Function Name: Pin_LRTx2_SetDriveMode

Note This affects all pins in the Pins component instance. Use the Per-Pin APIs if you wish to control individual pin's drive modes.

Parameters
modeMode for the selected signals. Valid options are documented in Drive mode constants.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic, the ISR can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component Drive Mode registers can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

uint8 Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_Read ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port (pin status register) and masks the required bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_Read

The pin's status register returns the current logic level present on the physical pin.

Returns
The current value for the pins in the component as a right justified number.

\funcusage

Definition at line 113 of file Pin_Reset_Ev_HW.c.

◆ Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_Read() API because the Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Definition at line 141 of file Pin_Reset_Ev_HW.c.

◆ Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_SetDriveMode()

void Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_SetDriveMode ( uint8  mode)

Sets the drive mode for each of the Pins component's pins.

Function Name: Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_SetDriveMode

Note This affects all pins in the Pins component instance. Use the Per-Pin APIs if you wish to control individual pin's drive modes.

Parameters
modeMode for the selected signals. Valid options are documented in Drive mode constants.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic, the ISR can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component Drive Mode registers can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

◆ Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_Write()

void Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_Write ( uint8  value)

Writes the value to the physical port (data output register), masking and shifting the bits appropriately.

File Name: Pin_Reset_Ev_HW.c
Version 2.20

Description: This file contains API to enable firmware control of a Pins component.

Note:

Copyright 2008-2015, Cypress Semiconductor Corporation. All rights reserved. You may use this file only in accordance with the license, terms, conditions, disclaimers, and limitations in the end user license agreement accompanying the software package with which this file was provided. Function Name: Pin_Reset_Ev_HW_Write

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This function avoids changing other bits in the port by using the appropriate method (read-modify-write or bit banding).

Note This function should not be used on a hardware digital output pin as it is driven by the hardware signal attached to it.

Parameters
valueValue to write to the component instance.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic; the Interrupt Service Routines (ISR) can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component data register can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

Definition at line 113 of file Pin_Sel2_Pwr.c.

◆ Pin_Sel2_Pwr_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_Sel2_Pwr_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_Sel2_Pwr_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_Sel2_Pwr_Read() API because the Pin_Sel2_Pwr_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

\funcusage

Definition at line 141 of file Pin_Sel2_Pwr.c.

File Name: Pin_Sel2_Pwr.c
Version 2.20

Description: This file contains API to enable firmware control of a Pins component.

Copyright 2008-2015, Cypress Semiconductor Corporation. All rights reserved. Function Name: Pin_Sel2_Pwr_Write

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This function avoids changing other bits in the port by using the appropriate method (read-modify-write or bit banding).

Note This function should not be used on a hardware digital output pin as it is driven by the hardware signal attached to it.

Parameters
valueValue to write to the component instance.
Returns
None

Note This function should not be used on a hardware digital output pin as it is driven by the hardware signal attached to it.

Parameters
valueValue to write to the component instance.
Returns
None

\sideeffect If you use read-modify-write operations that are not atomic; the Interrupt Service Routines (ISR) can cause corruption of this function. An ISR that interrupts this function and performs writes to the Pins component data register can cause corrupted port data. To avoid this issue, you should either use the Per-Pin APIs (primary method) or disable interrupts around this function.

\funcusage

Definition at line 57 of file Pin_Tsync.c.

◆ Pin_UARTRx_ReadDataReg()

uint8 Pin_UARTRx_ReadDataReg ( void  )

Reads the associated physical port's data output register and masks the correct bits according to the width and bit position of the component instance.

Function Name: Pin_UARTRx_ReadDataReg

The data output register controls the signal applied to the physical pin in conjunction with the drive mode parameter. This is not the same as the preferred Pin_UARTRx_Read() API because the Pin_UARTRx_ReadDataReg() reads the data register instead of the status register. For output pins this is a useful function to determine the value just written to the pin.

Returns
The current value of the data register masked and shifted into a right justified number for the component instance.

◆ USBUART_CD_Dp_ClearInterrupt()

uint8 USBUART_CD_Dp_ClearInterrupt ( void  )

Clears any active interrupts attached with the component and returns the value of the interrupt status register allowing determination of which pins generated an interrupt event.

Function Name: USBUART_CD_Dp_ClearInterrupt

Returns
The right-shifted current value of the interrupt status register. Each pin has one bit set if it generated an interrupt event. For example, bit 0 is for pin 0 and bit 1 is for pin 1 of the Pins component.

\sideeffect Clears all bits of the physical port's interrupt status register, not just those associated with the Pins component.

\funcusage

◆ USBUART_CD_Dp_SetInterruptMode()

void USBUART_CD_Dp_SetInterruptMode ( uint16  position,
uint16  mode 
)

Configures the interrupt mode for each of the Pins component's pins. Alternatively you may set the interrupt mode for all the pins specified in the Pins component.

Function Name: USBUART_CD_Dp_SetInterruptMode

Note The interrupt is port-wide and therefore any enabled pin interrupt may trigger it.

Parameters
positionThe pin position as listed in the Pins component. You may OR these to be able to configure the interrupt mode of multiple pins within a Pins component. Or you may use USBUART_CD_Dp_INTR_ALL to configure the interrupt mode of all the pins in the Pins component.
  • USBUART_CD_Dp_0_INTR (First pin in the list)
  • USBUART_CD_Dp_1_INTR (Second pin in the list)
  • ...
  • USBUART_CD_Dp_INTR_ALL (All pins in Pins component)
modeInterrupt mode for the selected pins. Valid options are documented in Interrupt constants.
Returns
None

\sideeffect It is recommended that the interrupt be disabled before calling this function to avoid unintended interrupt requests. Note that the interrupt type is port wide, and therefore will trigger for any enabled pin on the port.

\funcusage

Definition at line 187 of file USBUART_CD_Dp.c.

◆ USBUART_CD_Force()

void USBUART_CD_Force ( uint8  bState)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_Force This function forces a USB J, K, or SE0 state on the D+/D lines. It provides the necessary mechanism for a USB device application to perform a USB Remote Wakeup. For more information, see the USB 2.0 Specification for details on Suspend and Resume.

Parameters
stateA byte indicating which of the four bus states to enable. Symbolic names and their associated values are listed here:
State Description
USBUART_CD_FORCE_J Force a J State onto the D+/D lines
USBUART_CD_FORCE_K Force a K State onto the D+/D lines
USBUART_CD_FORCE_SE0 Force a Single Ended 0 onto the D+/D lines
USBUART_CD_FORCE_NONE Return bus to SIE control

Function Name: USBUART_CD_GetEPAckState This function determines whether an ACK transaction occurred on this endpoint by reading the ACK bit in the control register of the endpoint. It does not clear the ACK bit.

Parameters

Returns
If an ACKed transaction occurred, this function returns a non-zero value. Otherwise, it returns zero.

◆ USBUART_CD_GetEPCount()

uint16 USBUART_CD_GetEPCount ( uint8  epNumber)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_GetEPCount This function supports Data Endpoints only(EP1-EP8). Returns the transfer count for the requested endpoint. The value from the count registers includes 2 counts for the two byte checksum of the packet. This function subtracts the two counts.

Parameters
epNumberData Endpoint Number. Valid values are between 1 and 8.
Returns
Returns the current byte count from the specified endpoint or 0 for an invalid endpoint.

◆ USBUART_CD_GetEPState()

uint8 USBUART_CD_GetEPState ( uint8  epNumber)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_GetEPState This function returns the state of the requested endpoint.

Parameters
epNumberData endpoint number
Returns
Returns the current state of the specified USBFS endpoint. Symbolic names and their associated values are given in the following table. Use these constants whenever you write code to change the state of the endpoints, such as ISR code, to handle data sent or received.
Return Value Description
USBFS_NO_EVENT_PENDING The endpoint is awaiting SIE action
USBFS_EVENT_PENDING The endpoint is awaiting CPU action
USBFS_NO_EVENT_ALLOWED The endpoint is locked from access
USBFS_IN_BUFFER_FULL The IN endpoint is loaded and the mode is set to ACK IN
USBFS_IN_BUFFER_EMPTY An IN transaction occurred and more data can be loaded
USBFS_OUT_BUFFER_EMPTY The OUT endpoint is set to ACK OUT and is waiting for data
USBFS_OUT_BUFFER_FULL An OUT transaction has occurred and data can be read

                               regulator depending on the power supply

                               For PSoC 3/5LP devices, the VDDD supply
                               voltage is considered and for PSoC 4A-L,
                               the VBUS supply voltage is considered.

◆ USBUART_CD_IsConfigurationChanged()

uint8 USBUART_CD_IsConfigurationChanged ( void  )

Function Name: USBUART_CD_IsConfigurationChanged This function returns the clear-on-read configuration state. It is useful when the host sends double SET_CONFIGURATION request with the same configuration number or changes alternate settings of the interface. After configuration has been changed the OUT endpoints must be enabled and IN endpoint must be loaded with data to start communication with the host.

Returns
None-zero value when new configuration has been changed, otherwise zero is returned.

\globalvars

USBUART_CD_configurationChanged - This variable is set to 1 after a SET_CONFIGURATION request and cleared in this function.

◆ USBUART_CD_LoadInEP()

void USBUART_CD_LoadInEP ( uint8  epNumber,
const uint8  pData[],
uint16  length 
)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_LoadInEP This function performs different functionality depending on the Components configured Endpoint Buffer Management. This parameter is defined in the Descriptor Root in Component Configure window.

Manual (Static/Dynamic Allocation): This function loads and enables the specified USB data endpoint for an IN data transfer.

DMA with Manual Buffer Management: Configures DMA for a data transfer from system RAM to endpoint buffer. Generates request for a transfer.

DMA with Automatic Buffer Management: Configures DMA. This is required only once, so it is done only when parameter pData is not NULL. When the pData pointer is NULL, the function skips this task. Sets Data ready status: This generates the first DMA transfer and prepares data in endpoint buffer.

Parameters
epNumberContains the data endpoint number. Valid values are between 1 and 8.
*pDataA pointer to a data array from which the data for the endpoint space is loaded.
lengthThe number of bytes to transfer from the array and then send as a result of an IN request. Valid values are between 0 and 512 (1023 for DMA with Automatic Buffer Management mode). The value 512 is applicable if only one endpoint is used.

\reentrant No.

Definition at line 1342 of file USBUART_CD.c.

◆ USBUART_CD_ReadOutEP()

uint16 USBUART_CD_ReadOutEP ( uint8  epNumber,
uint8  pData[],
uint16  length 
)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_ReadOutEP This function performs different functionality depending on the Components configured Endpoint Buffer Management. This parameter is defined in the Descriptor Root in Component Configure window.

Manual (Static/Dynamic Allocation): This function moves the specified number of bytes from endpoint buffer to system RAM. The number of bytes actually transferred from endpoint buffer to system RAM is the lesser of the actual number of bytes sent by the host or the number of bytes requested by the length parameter.

DMA with Manual Buffer Management: Configure DMA to transfer data from endpoint buffer to system RAM. Generate a DMA request. The firmware must wait until the DMA completes the data transfer after calling the USBUART_CD_ReadOutEP() API. For example, by checking EPstate:

The USBFS_EnableOutEP() has to be called to allow host to write data into the endpoint buffer after DMA has completed transfer data from OUT endpoint buffer to SRAM.

DMA with Automatic Buffer Management: Configure DMA. This is required only once and automatically generates DMA requests as data arrives

Parameters
epNumberContains the data endpoint number. Valid values are between 1 and 8.
pDataA pointer to a data array from which the data for the endpoint space is loaded.
lengthThe number of bytes to transfer from the USB Out endpoint and loads it into data array. Valid values are between 0 and 1023. The function moves fewer than the requested number of bytes if the host sends fewer bytes than requested.
Returns
Number of bytes received, 0 for an invalid endpoint.

\reentrant No.

Definition at line 1653 of file USBUART_CD.c.

◆ USBUART_CD_SetPowerStatus()

void USBUART_CD_SetPowerStatus ( uint8  powerStatus)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_SetPowerStatus This function sets the current power status. The device replies to USB GET_STATUS requests based on this value. This allows the device to properly report its status for USB Chapter 9 compliance. Devices can change their power source from self powered to bus powered at any time and report their current power source as part of the device status. You should call this function any time your device changes from self powered to bus powered or vice versa, and set the status appropriately.

Parameters
powerStatusContains the desired power status, one for self powered or zero for bus powered. Symbolic names and their associated values are given here:
Power Status Description
USBUART_CD_DEVICE_STATUS_BUS_POWERED Set the device to bus powered
USBUART_CD_DEVICE_STATUS_SELF_POWERED Set the device to self powered

\globalvars

USBUART_CD_deviceStatus - set power status

\reentrant No.

◆ USBUART_CD_Start()

void USBUART_CD_Start ( uint8  device,
uint8  mode 
)

Function Name: USBUART_CD_Start This function performs all required initialization for the USBFS component. After this function call, the USB device initiates communication with the host by pull-up D+ line. This is the preferred method to begin component operation.

Note that global interrupts have to be enabled because interrupts are required for USBFS component operation.

PSoC 4200L devices: when USBFS component configured to DMA with Automatic Buffer Management, the DMA interrupt priority is changed to the highest (priority 0) inside this function.

PSoC 3/PSoC 5LP devices: when USBFS component configured to DMA with Automatic Buffer Management, the Arbiter interrupt priority is changed to the highest (priority 0) inside this function.

Parameters
deviceContains the device number of the desired device descriptor. The device number can be found in the Device Descriptor Tab of "Configure" dialog, under the settings of desired Device Descriptor, in the "Device Number" field.
modeThe operating voltage. This determines whether the voltage regulator is enabled for 5V operation or if pass through mode is used for 3.3V operation. Symbolic names and their associated values are given in the following list. 
*USBUART_CD_3V_OPERATION* - Disable voltage regulator and pass-
                               through Vcc for pull-up

*USBUART_CD_5V_OPERATION* - Enable voltage regulator and use
                               regulator for pull-up

*USBUART_CD_DWR_POWER_OPERATION* - Enable or disable the voltage
                               regulator depending on the power supply
                               voltage configuration in the DWR tab.
                               For PSoC 3/5LP devices, the VDDD supply
                               voltage is considered and for PSoC 4A-L,
                               the VBUS supply voltage is considered.*
\globalvars USBUART_CD_initVar

\sideeffect This function will reset all communication states to default.

\reentrant No.
